
  <sn><md>### JavaScript `Array.splice()` Method

The `Array.splice()` method is one of the most versatile and powerful array manipulation tools in JavaScript. It allows developers to **add**, **remove**, or **replace** elements within an array—directly modifying the original array.


:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Syntax :**

```javascript
array.splice(start, deleteCount, item1, item2, ...)
```

**Key Characteristics :**

* **Modifies the original array** (in contrast to methods like `slice()` that return a new array).
* Can be used for **insertion**, **deletion**, or **replacement** of elements.
* Returns the **removed elements** as a new array.

**Returns:**
An array containing the **deleted elements** (if any).
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6

**Parameters:**

| Parameter                        | Description                                                                       |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **start**                        | The index at which to start changing the array.                                   |
| **deleteCount (optional)**       | The number of elements to remove from the array. If `0`, no elements are removed. |
| **item1, item2, ... (optional)** | The elements to add to the array starting at the `start` index.                   |

:::
:::
